  <section id="learn" class="page">
    <h2 class="section-title">What is ambulance balance billing?</h2>
    <p class="section-subtitle">
      You don&rsquo;t get to choose which ambulance shows up when you dial 911. But if that ambulance is out-of-network,
      you can still be billed for the difference between what the company charges and what your insurer decides to pay.
    </p>

    <div class="columns">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>1. Emergency → out-of-network ride</h3>
        <p>
          In most cities, the ambulance that responds is determined by dispatch, not by you.
          Many of those providers are not in your insurance network, even for people with solid coverage.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>2. Insurer pays part of the bill</h3>
        <p>
          Your insurer pays what it thinks the ride should cost &mdash; often far less than the ambulance company charges.
          There is no standard pricing, and billed amounts can be thousands of dollars.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>3. You get the “balance bill”</h3>
        <p>
          The ambulance company then bills <em>you</em> for the rest: the balance.
          Patients are left with huge, unexpected invoices, aggressive collection tactics, and damaged credit
          &mdash; all for doing the right thing in an emergency.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

